Early in the morning, the first time Detective Arin Kale met his own dead body, it was raining.

Not the poetic kind of rain—the kind that felt like static on your skin, sharp and electric. It fell in rigid lines across the alley behind 7th Street, where neon signs flickered like dying stars. Arin shrinked to his knees beside the body, ignoring the officers whispering behind him.

“Sir… you shouldn’t be this close,” one of them said.

Arin didn’t answer. He was staring at the dead man’s face.

Same scar across the eyebrow. Same worn leather jacket. Same eyes—except these were empty.

“Time of death?” he asked quietly.

“Approximately… six hours from now.”

The officer winced after saying it, as if the sentence itself might break something fragile.

Arin stood slowly. “Seal the area. Nobody touches him.”

Nobody asked the obvious question: If he’s dead in six hours, what happens now?

Because everyone already knew the answer.

Time Crimes Division existed for exactly this reason.

Back at headquarters, the walls hummed with quiet machinery—chrono-stabilizers, temporal anchors, devices that tried to make sense of a universe that refused to stay linear.

Arin walked straight into the briefing room, tossing his coat aside.

“Run the loop,” he said.

A technician hesitated. “You might not like what you see.”

“I already don’t.”

The screen flickered to life.

Footage from a street cam. Timestamp: +5 hours 12 minutes.

There he was—Arin—walking into the alley. Alone.

Then a flash. Not light. More like… reality glitching.

And then—he collapsed.

No attacker. No weapon. Just… dead.

The video froze.

“Cause?” Arin asked.

“Unknown,” said the technician. “No external trauma. Internal systems just… shut down.”

Arin leaned back, exhaling slowly. “So I walk into an alley and die for no reason.”

“Not exactly,” another voice said.

Dr. Meera Sanyal stepped forward—the division’s temporal physicist, and the only person who spoke about time like it was a stubborn animal instead of a rule.

“You don’t die for no reason,” she said. “You die because you’re supposed to.”

Arin gave a dry laugh. “That’s comforting.”

She ignored the sarcasm. “Your death is a fixed point.”

“Meaning?”

“Meaning if you don’t die there… something worse replaces it.”

Silence filled the room.

Arin crossed his arms. “Define worse.”

Meera met his eyes. “We don’t know. That’s the problem with breaking fixed points—you don’t get to preview the consequences.”

Arin had spent ten years chasing criminals who used time like a weapon—smugglers, assassins, people who rewrote history for profit.

He’d always believed one thing: everything has a cause.

Now he was staring at a death with none.

Or worse—a cause that hadn’t happened yet.

Three hours later, Arin stood outside the alley.

The rain hadn’t started yet. The sky was too still, like it was holding its breath.

In his ear, Meera’s voice crackled through the comm.

“You still have time to walk away.”

“And let myself die?”

“Yes.”

He smirked faintly. “You’re terrible at motivational speeches.”

“I’m serious, Arin. If this is a fixed point—”

“Then I’ll fix it,” he said, and stepped forward.

The alley was empty.

No body. No officers. No future yet.

Just silence.

Arin moved slowly, every sense sharp. He checked corners, scanned shadows, listened for anything out of place.

Nothing.

Then—

A flicker.

Not in front of him.

Behind.

He turned.

And froze.

Another man stood there.

Same height. Same face.

Same scar.

But older. Tired. Eyes carrying something heavy.

“Hello, Arin,” the man said.

Arin stared. “You’ve got to be kidding me.”

The older version smiled faintly. “I thought the same thing the first time.”

“The first time?”

“You’re not the first loop.”

That landed harder than anything else.

Arin’s voice hardened. “Explain. Now.”

The older Arin stepped closer. “You’ve tried to stop this before. Every version of you does.”

“And?”

“And every time, you fail.”

Rain began to fall.

That sharp, static rain.

Arin felt it against his skin. Same as before.

“So what—this is inevitable?” he snapped. “I just stand here and drop dead?”

“Not exactly,” said the older one. “You don’t die because something attacks you.”

“Then why?”

The older Arin hesitated.

For the first time, he looked afraid.

“Because I kill you.”

Silence.

The kind that feels like the world just skipped a heartbeat.

Arin let out a slow breath. “That doesn’t make any sense.”

“It does,” the older one said. “You’re about to discover something—something about how time actually works. And when you do… you’ll realize this is the only way.”

“The only way for what?”

The older Arin didn’t answer immediately.

Instead, he pulled out a small device—sleek, metallic, humming faintly.

A temporal trigger.

Arin’s eyes narrowed. “You’re going to erase me.”

“No,” said the older one. “I’m going to preserve everything else.”

The rain intensified.

Arin’s mind raced. “What happens if you don’t do this?”

The older Arin looked past him, as if seeing something far worse than death.

“I tried that once,” he said softly.

“And?”

“You don’t want to know.”

“I do.”

A pause.

Then, quietly:

“Time doesn’t break cleanly. It rots.”

Arin took a step forward. “There has to be another way.”

“There isn’t.”

“You don’t know that.”

“I do,” the older one snapped, emotion finally breaking through. “Because I’ve watched the alternative!”

The alley seemed to bend slightly, like reality itself was listening.

“People vanish,” he continued. “Not die—unhappen. Entire cities glitch out of existence. History contradicts itself until nothing makes sense anymore.”

He looked back at Arin.

“This moment—your death—it’s holding everything together.”

Arin clenched his jaw.

Detective instincts screamed at him: find another angle, another clue, another suspect.

But there was no suspect.

Just himself.

“So that’s it?” he said. “I just accept this?”

The older Arin stepped closer, lowering the device.

“I didn’t accept it either,” he said quietly. “That’s why I’m here.”

Arin frowned. “What do you mean?”

A faint smile.

“Every loop, I hesitate.”

The rain slowed.

The world held still.

“And one day,” the older Arin said, “one version of us will figure out something different.”

He placed the device in Arin’s hand.

“Maybe it’s you.”

The alley flickered.

Two Arins stood facing each other, both alive.

For the first time, the loop had changed.

And somewhere—far beyond that alley—

Time noticed.